{[%evp 0,29,16,16,17,17,17,17,59,42,68,55,54,29,79,60,60,57,53,41,45,33,49,25,49,49,30,30,30,27,27,27]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {Besides the main symmetrical answer, Black has a few minor options. Anyway, precision is required from White when facing them.} g6 {looks relatively sound, but all Black can get is a bad version of the Scotch. It was astonishing to find out that some top players like Mamedyarov, MVL, Shirov and Kamsky have opted for it.} (3... Bc5 4. Nxe5 $1 {A typical and strong reply, Black is losing the fight for the center.} Nxe5 (4... Bxf2+ $143 5. Kxf2 Nxe5 6. d4 $16) 5. d4 Bd6 6. dxe5 Bxe5 7. Bd3 Nf6 (7... d6 8. O-O Qh4 9. f4 Bd4+ 10. Kh1 Bxc3 11. bxc3 $16) 8. O-O d6 (8... O-O 9. Bg5 $1 ({it is early for} 9. f4 Bd4+ 10. Kh1 d6 {with mutual chances}) 9... c6 10. f4 Bxc3 11. bxc3 d5 12. e5 Qb6+ 13. Kh1 Ne4 14. Qh5 $1 ({more demanding than} 14. Bxe4 dxe4 15. f5 Qc5 16. Qd4 Qxd4 17. cxd4 $14 {Narayanan - Aradhya, Noida, 2016}) 14... Nxg5 15. Qxg5 f6 16. Qh5 f5 17. Rab1 Qc7 (17... Qa5 18. g4 $1 $18) 18. Rf3 Be6 19. Rg3 $16) 9. Ne2 ({another idea to harass Be5 can be seen in} 9. Qe1 $5 O-O 10. f4 $40) 9... Nd7 $1 {is relatively the best outcome but after} (9... d5 10. f4 Bd6 11. e5 Bc5+ 12. Kh1 Ne4 (12... Ng4 {backfired badly after} 13. Qe1 $1 O-O 14. h3 Ne3 15. Bxe3 Bxe3 16. Qg3 Bc5 17. f5 f6 18. e6 $18 {in Rudzinska - Dounis, Chess.com INT, 2022}) 13. f5 Nf2+ 14. Rxf2 Bxf2 15. Nf4 O-O 16. f6 $18) 10. f4 Bf6 11. Ng3 Nc5 12. Be3 Nxd3 13. cxd3 $40 {White has a strong initiative for free.}) (3... Bb4 {looks like a lesser evil, but Black is objectively far from equalizing after} 4. Nd5 $1 Bc5 5. Nxe5 $1 {This common tactical motif is working properly again:} Bxf2+ (5... Nxe5 6. d4 c6 7. Ne3 Nf6 (7... Bb4+ 8. c3 Ng6 9. cxb4 $16) 8. dxc5 Qa5+ (8... O-O $6 9. Qd4 $18 {L. Sokolin - R. Aukhatov, Chess.com INT, 2022}) 9. c3 Qxc5 {and White manages to fix the advantage with the help of the concrete} 10. Nf5 $1 O-O $140 11. Be3 Qa5 12. Nd6 $16) 6. Kxf2 Nxe5 7. d4 {As usual in such lines, Black has little to show for the opponent's central preponderance and his pair of mighty bishops.} Ng6 8. Qf3 $5 c6 9. Ne3 Nf6 (9... d5 10. exd5 Nf6 11. Bd3 O-O 12. Rf1 cxd5 {transposes to the note for 12.Rf1, see below}) 10. Bd3 d5 (10... O-O 11. Rf1 Nh4 12. Qg3 d5 13. exd5 cxd5 14. Kg1 $16) 11. exd5 cxd5 12. b3 (12. Rf1 $5 O-O 13. Kg1 $16) 12... O-O 13. Rf1 Qb6 14. Ba3 Re8 15. Bc5 $16) (3... d6 {is more solid -} 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 {can lead to a variation in the Ruy Lopez after} 6. Bb5 {, see Chapter 3.} ({Instead, an alternative is} 6. Nxc6 $5 bxc6 7. Bd3 Be7 8. f4 O-O 9. O-O $16)) 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bg7 6. Be3 ({White is better after the other option} 6. Nxc6 $5 bxc6 7. Bc4 {as well, for example} d6 8. O-O Be6 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Qd3 Qd7 11. b3 $5 Nh6 (11... Ne7 12. Bb2 O-O 13. Rad1 Rf7 14. Na4 $16) 12. Bd2 O-O 13. f3 ({in case of the direct} 13. Rae1 c5 {White can also consider the more ambitious} 14. f4 $16) 13... c5 14. Rae1 $16 {Conde Poderoso - Velker, ICCF email, 2018.}) 6... Nf6 (6... Nge7 7. Qd2 O-O 8. O-O-O d6 {is inviting the typical} 9. h4 h5 10. f3 Ne5 11. Bh6 $16 {Kobalia - Mamedyarov, Wch Blitz, Khanty-Mansiysk, 2013.}) 7. Nxc6 $5 bxc6 (7... dxc6 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. O-O-O+ Bd7 10. f3 $16) 8. e5 Ng8 9. f4 d6 (9... Nh6 10. Qf3 $1 O-O 11. O-O-O $16) 10. Qf3 $1 Ne7 11. O-O-O O-O 12. Bc4 ({The harsh} 12. g4 $2 {was justified after} Qd7 $2 (12... Nd5 $1 13. Bd2 Rb8 $132) 13. Rg1 f5 14. g5 $18 {Remizov - Shirov, Chess.com INT, 2020.}) 12... Be6 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. Qh3 Qc8 15. Ne4 $16 {The position is still very tense, but it is objectively much better for White, Caruso - Eintalu, ICCF email, 2018.} *

