{[%evp 0,31,17,17,10,17,12,17,24,-10,97,24,24,-32,48,31,40,45,45,29,53,62,60,64,70,36,34,45,50,47,47,54,66,57]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 Bb4 {Mamedyarov played this on several occasions but had difficulties in equalizing.} 5. Nxe5 Qe7 {The main reply.} (5... Nxe4 $6 6. Qg4 $1 {looks very sharp, but it leads to better endgames in most branches.} Nxc3 7. Qxg7 Rf8 ({the attractive} 7... Qf6 {does not bring any relief either -} 8. Qxf6 Nd5+ 9. c3 Nxf6 10. Nxc6 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 dxc6 12. f3 Be6 13. c4 Nd7 14. Be3 Nb6 15. Rc1 O-O-O 16. Kf2 $16 {Kravtsiv - Lodhi, Al Ain, 2012}) 8. a3 $1 Ba5 (8... Nxd4 9. axb4 $18) 9. Nxc6 (9. Bh6 $2 {is tempting, but wrong -} Qe7 10. Bd3 (10. Qxf8+ Qxf8 11. Bxf8 Kxf8 12. Nc4 Nd5+ 13. Nxa5 Nxa5 14. O-O-O d6 $17) 10... d6 11. O-O dxe5 12. bxc3 Bxc3 $19 {and White soon resigned in Duhless - mersad_98, Chess.com, 2019}) 9... dxc6 10. Qe5+ (10. Bd2 $5 Qe7+ 11. Qe5 Qxe5+ 12. dxe5 Bf5 13. bxc3 O-O-O 14. O-O-O Rd5 15. f4 $16) 10... Qe7 11. Qxe7+ Kxe7 12. Bd2 Bf5 13. bxc3 Bxc2 14. Be2 $1 (14. c4 Bxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Bf5 16. Bd3 Bxd3 17. Kxd3 Rad8 $14) 14... Rae8 15. h4 Kd7 16. Kf1 b5 17. g4 Bb6 18. Rh3 $16 {Black has too many weaknesses and a very static queenside structure.}) (5... O-O $6 {is the favourite move of one of the most creative GMs - Timur Gareyev - but it can hardly be labelled as a good one.} 6. Nxc6 dxc6 7. e5 Ne4 (7... Nd5 8. Bd2 $16) 8. Qd3 (8. a3 $6 {is too optimistic -} Nxc3 9. Qd3 $2 (9. Qd2 Nb5 10. axb4 Nxd4 $13) 9... Nd5+ $1 ({much better than} 9... Ba5 $2 10. bxc3 Bf5 11. Qe3 c5 12. Bd2 $13 {dropstoneDP - TimurGareyev, Chess.com, 2022}) 10. axb4 Nxb4 11. Qb3 Qxd4 $19) 8... Bf5 9. a3 $1 {leads to semi-forced sequence and a favourable endgame for White -} Qd7 (9... Bg6 10. axb4 Nxf2 11. Qc4 Nxh1 12. g3 Bxc2 13. Be3 $16) 10. Qf3 $1 Ba5 11. Bd3 Nxc3 12. Bxf5 Na4+ 13. c3 Qxd4 14. O-O Qxe5 15. Qh5 $1 g6 16. Bxg6 Qxh5 17. Bxh5 $16 {White's structure is much better than the two bishops.}) (5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qe7 7. f3 $1 ({but not} 7. Qd3 $2 Nxe5 8. dxe5 Qxe5 $15) 7... Nxe5 8. dxe5 Qxe5 9. Qd4 $14 {transposes to the 6.f3-subline, see the next note.}) 6. Qd3 $1 {looks a bit artificial, but it is objectively the only way to obtain the pair of bishops without spoiling the queenside structure.} (6. f3 {is the main alternative and now:} Nxe5 $1 ({Contrary to the leading text, here} 6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Nxe5 8. dxe5 Qxe5 {is the less precise option in the view of} 9. Qd4 {, taking advantage of the overprotection of the central pawn.} d6 10. a4 {According to the existing games, White can exert pressure:} O-O (10... a5 11. Rb1 b6 12. Bb5+ Bd7 13. Kf2 $1 (13. O-O O-O 14. Qxe5 dxe5 15. Bxd7 Nxd7 16. Be3 Rfd8 $132) 13... Rd8 14. Qxe5+ dxe5 15. c4 $1 ({an improvement upon} 15. Ke3 Bxb5 16. Rxb5 Nd7 17. Ba3 h5 $132 {A. Das - A. Demchenko, Teplice, 2022}) 15... Bxb5 16. Rxb5 Nd7 17. Be3 Ke7 18. Rhb1 Ra8 19. h4 $14) 11. Qxe5 dxe5 12. Ba3 Re8 (12... Rd8 13. Bc4 Be6 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. Ke2 $16) 13. a5 $1 (13. Bb5 $6 Bd7 14. O-O-O $6 {proved ungrounded after the simple} Bxb5 15. axb5 a6 {, leaving White searching for questionable compensation after} 16. b6 cxb6 17. Rd6 b5 18. Rb6 Rac8 $15 {dropstoneDP - SGchess01, Chess.com, 2022}) 13... Bd7 14. Kf2 $5 (14. Bc4 Be6 (14... b6 $5 {deserves attention, with ideas for pushing the pawn to the c5-square or to open some files on the queenside, for instance} 15. Kf2 bxa5 16. g4 a4 17. Rhd1 Bc6 18. h4 $44) 15. Bb5 Bd7 16. Bd3 a6 ({here} 16... b6 $5 {can be recommended as well}) 17. Kf2 Bc6 18. Rhd1 Rad8 19. Ke3 Nd7 20. Bc4 Nf8 21. Rab1 Ne6 22. Bxe6 $1 fxe6 23. c4 $16 {dropstoneDP - Azerichess, Chess.com, 2022}) 14... b6 15. Bb4 c5 16. Ba3 Be6 17. Be2 Rab8 18. Bc1 Rec8 19. Be3 $16) 7. dxe5 Qxe5 {is the right move order, with the idea for} 8. Bd2 d5 $1 $132) (6. Nxc6 Qxe4+ 7. Be2 dxc6 8. O-O Qh4 {is double-edged, dropstoneDP - 1tsNowOrNever, Chess.com, 2022.}) 6... Bxc3+ ({The position after} 6... Nxe5 7. dxe5 Qxe5 8. Bd2 {is venomous for Black -} O-O (8... Bxc3 $6 9. Bxc3 Qxe4+ 10. Qxe4+ Nxe4 11. Bxg7 Rg8 12. Bd4 $16 {, as in dropstoneDP - BlackGod93, Chess. com, 2022, is a strategical failure for the second player}) 9. O-O-O Bxc3 ({the modest} 9... d6 10. f4 {and now} Qa5 $6 {has dropped a piece after} 11. a3 $1 Bxa3 12. Nd5 $1 Bxb2+ 13. Kxb2 {and} Qc5 $6 14. Be3 {forced an immediate resignation in Duhless - TigranLPetrosyan, Chess.com, 2018, for on the only available square the queen will be trapped by 15.Ra1}) 10. Bxc3 Qf4+ 11. Rd2 (11. Kb1 $2 Nxe4 12. Bd4 $2 Nxf2 $17 {dropstoneDP - Arseniii_Nesterov, lichess. org, 2021}) 11... d5 (11... Re8 12. f3 d5 13. g3 Qh6 14. e5 $16) 12. exd5 Re8 13. b3 Ne4 14. Qd4 $1 Qh6 15. Bb5 $1 {A brilliant intermediate move practically refuting Black's operation.} Nxc3 16. Qxc3 Re7 17. Kb2 $18 {D. Cook - K. Dudeney, ICCF email, 2015.}) (6... Nxd4 7. Qxd4 Bc5 {is another way to regain the pawn, the critical position arises after} 8. Qd3 Qxe5 9. Be3 Bxe3 10. Qxe3 d6 11. O-O-O O-O {and now:} 12. f4 $5 {is simpler and stronger -} (12. f3 Bd7 13. g4 Bc6 14. h4 Rfe8 15. h5 h6 16. Rg1 Nh7 $2 ({an obvious concession, instead,} 16... Qg5 $1 17. Qxg5 $140 hxg5 18. b4 Re5 $132 {is satisfactory for Black}) 17. f4 Qe6 18. g5 $18 {jefferyx - PavelShkapenko, Chess.com, 2021}) 12... Qa5 13. Be2 Re8 14. Rd4 Bd7 15. Rhd1 Bc6 16. a4 $5 a6 (16... Qf5 17. Bf3 Qe6 18. h3 a6 19. g4 $16) 17. g4 b5 18. b4 Qb6 19. a5 $18) 7. Qxc3 Nxe4 8. Qe3 $1 ({Better than} 8. Nxc6 dxc6 9. Qe3 {because of} O-O $1 (9... Nd6 {does not seriously challenge White's move order -} 10. Qxe7+ Kxe7 11. Bf4 $14 {dropstoneDP - 1tsNowOrNever, Chess.com, 2022}) 10. Be2 Re8 $132) 8... Nd6 9. c3 Nf5 10. Nxc6 dxc6 11. Qxe7+ Kxe7 {So far dropstoneDP -1tsNowOrNever, Chess. com, 2022, when} 12. Bg5+ $5 f6 13. Bf4 {is a natural improvement -} Nd6 14. Bd3 Be6 15. Kd2 a5 16. Rhe1 $14 {and, due to the permanent weakness on c7, this endgame is quite unpleasant for Black.} *

