{[%evp 0,27,23,10,17,24,24,25,26,0,72,45,40,40,27,27,47,33,27,20,20,8,12,-15,0,-4,25,33,20,0]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 {Apart from 4...exd4 and 4...Bb4 it is difficult to point at another reliable alternative. However, some of these rare deviations are enjoying popularity even at GM level.} d6 {For instance, this is the pet choice of GM Zoran Jovanovic.} (4... d5 $6 {looks attractive, but this is the only positive merit of the move -} 5. Nxe5 Nxe4 (5... dxe4 6. Bb5 Bd7 7. Nxd7 Qxd7 8. d5 a6 9. dxc6 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 O-O-O+ 11. Ke2 axb5 12. cxb7+ Kxb7 13. Nxb5 $16) 6. Nxe4 (6. Qh5 $5 Nxe5 7. Qxe5+ Be6 8. Nxe4 dxe4 9. Qxe4 $16) 6... dxe4 7. Bb5 Bd7 (7... a6 8. Ba4 Qd6 9. Bf4 $16) 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Qe2 $16 {White will have a sound extra pawn.}) (4... Bd6 $2 {is considered a very decent reply to 4.Bb5, but here it is dubious in the view of} 5. dxe5 Nxe5 6. Nb5 $1 Nxf3+ 7. gxf3 $1 Bb4+ 8. Bd2 Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2 a6 10. Nc3 O-O 11. O-O-O $16 {R. Marques - J. Diaz Hermida, ICCF email, 2019}) (4... Nxd4 $6 5. Nxd4 exd4 6. Qxd4 d6 7. Bf4 Be7 8. O-O-O O-O 9. f3 Be6 10. Kb1 $16) 5. Bb5 {Black is facing an unpleasant choice - to play some passive version of the Pirc or to transpose to Steinitz defence in the Ruy Lopez.} (5. dxe5 $5 Nxe5 (5... dxe5 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. Bg5 Ke8 8. O-O-O Bd6 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Bb5 $16) 6. Bf4 $1 {is the acid test for Black:} (6. Nxe5 dxe5 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bc4 {is well countered with} Bb4 (8... Be6 $143 $6 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. f3 $16 {dropstoneDP - daro94, Chess.com, 2022}) 9. Bd2 Ke7 10. a3 Bc5 $132) 6... Ng6 (6... Nxf3+ 7. Qxf3 Be7 8. h3 $1 ({it is not easy to neutralize} 8. Be2 {either -} Bg4 9. Qd3 Bxe2 10. Qxe2 O-O 11. O-O-O $40 {D. Paravyan - Z. Jovanovic, Lichess.org INT, 2020}) 8... O-O 9. O-O-O $16 {Asis Gargatagli - Anton Guijarro, Linares, 2015}) 7. Bg3 Be7 8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O $40) (5. d5 Ne7 {is also possible, but it is less to my liking than the other two alternatives.}) 5... exd4 {Black can hardly postpone this capture for long.} (5... Bd7 6. d5 ({A straightforward idea to exchange the light-square bishops and initiate expansion on the queenside, White can also pay attention to the Nimzowitsch's} 6. Bxc6 $5 Bxc6 $140 7. Qe2 exd4 8. Nxd4 $16 {G. Quparadze - T. Petrosian, Yerevan, 2021}) 6... Ne7 7. Bxd7+ Nxd7 8. O-O g6 9. a4 a6 10. a5 $16 {dropstoneDP - VeryMasculineEgirl, Chess.com 2021.}) 6. Nxd4 Bd7 7. O-O Be7 8. Nxc6 $5 Bxc6 (8... bxc6 9. Bd3 O-O 10. f4 $16) 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. f4 O-O 11. b3 d5 12. e5 Bb4 13. Qd3 $1 ({A possible improvement on} 13. Qf3 Qe7 14. Kh1 Bxc3 15. Qxc3 Ne4 16. Qxc6 Qe6 $14 {Pasko - De Oliveira, Marczell Memorial email, 2016.}) 13... Nd7 (13... Bxc3 14. Qxc3 Ne4 15. Qxc6 $18) 14. Ne2 $16 {White is strategically better on both flanks.} *

