{[%evp 0,49,21,26,26,26,57,18,24,2,2,2,12,16,26,-10,-3,1,15,-13,-22,-10,26,-5,6,8,18,-4,13,-32,-59,26,66,33,93,91,103,-238,2,38,86,87,-50,43,43,10,10,36,39,21,38,35]} 1. e4 Nc6 ({Obviously, our move order is} 1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Nxe4 {transposing to our line.}) 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Nxe4 $5 {This drastic approach has become popular even at the highest level.} 6. Nxe4 Qe7 7. Bd3 $5 {This gambit idea is the most principled and stylish reaction.} (7. f3 {is considered to be the main line. Black's position looks ugly in many cases, but it is not easy to prove an advantage with concrete moves.} d5 8. Bb5 Bd7 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. O-O dxe4 {dropstoneDP - pheonixking2000, Chess.com, 2022.}) 7... Nxd4 (7... d5 $4 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. O-O dxe4 10. Bxe4 Bd7 11. Re1 (11. Bf4 $5 $18) 11... O-O-O 12. Qd3 $18 {Duhless - pheonixking2000, Chess.com, 2022.}) 8. O-O {Now Black has two options.} d5 (8... Ne6 9. Bc4 $1 $146 {This novelty for developing a long-term initiative is appealing to me.} (9. Re1 $5 d5 10. Ng3 g6 (10... Qf6 11. Nh5 Qh4 12. g3 Qh3 13. Nf4 Qh6 14. Nxd5 Qh3 15. Nxc7+ {turned into a disaster for Black in jefferyx - profaVa, Chess.com, 2022}) 11. f4 $1 f5 12. Nxf5 gxf5 13. Bxf5 Qf6 $1 {looks incredibly dangerous, but Black will survive and transpose to only a slightly worse endgame.} (13... Qc5+ $2 14. Kh1 Be7 15. Qh5+ Kd8 16. Bxe6 $18 {Xiong - Zierk, Titled Tuesday intern op 12th Apr Early Chess.com INT blitz, 2022}) 14. Qxd5 c6 (14... Kf7 $5 {is another way for those players looking for some adrenaline}) 15. Qxe6+ Bxe6 16. Rxe6+ Qxe6 17. Bxe6 Bc5+ 18. Kf1 Rd8 19. Bg4 $14) (9. f4 $6 f5 10. Ng5 g6 $132) 9... c6 ({it is hard to believe in} 9... Qh4 $6 10. Re1 Be7 11. g3 Qh3 12. Bf1 Qf5 13. Bd3 {with huge attack}) 10. Bxe6 $1 ({a natural improvement over} 10. Bb3 $2 d5 11. Ng3 g6 $17 {dropstoneDP - OhanyanEminChess, lichess. org, 2021}) 10... dxe6 (10... fxe6 11. Bf4 d5 12. Nd6+ Kd7 13. Bg3 $1 e5 14. Nc4 $18) 11. Qh5 $1 Qc7 (11... Qb4 12. Qe5 $1 Qb5 13. Qc7 Qb6 14. Qg3 $16) 12. Bg5 $1 Be7 ({in case of} 12... Qa5 13. Rfd1 Be7 14. Rd3 h6 15. Rad1 O-O {White is breaking through with the help of} 16. b4 $1 Qf5 $1 17. g4 $1 Qxe4 18. Bxe7 Re8 19. Rd8) 13. f4 $1 O-O 14. Bf6 Bxf6 15. Nxf6+ gxf6 16. Rf3 Qb6+ 17. Kh1 Qxb2 18. Re1 Qxc2 19. Rg3+ Qg6 20. Ree3 Kh8 21. Rxg6 fxg6 22. Qd1 $40 {[%cal Gh1h4] Black has got enough material for the queen, but he is once again experiencing problems in the mobilization of his queenside.}) 9. Ng5 ({The desire to be wittier than the opponent by replying to his original} 9. Bc4 $5 {with} Nf3+ $5 10. Qxf3 Qxe4 {did not entirely solve the opening problems after} 11. Bxd5 Qxf3 12. Bxf3 c6 13. Re1+ Be7 14. Bg5 Be6 15. Bxe7 Kxe7 16. Bg4 Rad8 17. Bxe6 fxe6 18. Re2 Rd6 $14 {/= jefferyx - Fandorine, Chess.com, 2022.}) 9... Ne6 ({White's pressure is increasing after} 9... Be6 10. Be3 Nc6 11. Bb5 Qd6 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. c4 $36) 10. Re1 h6 (10... Bd7 11. Bf5 O-O-O 12. Qxd5 h6 {does not achieve full equality after} 13. Nxe6 $1 ({better than} 13. Nxf7 Qxf7 14. Rxe6 {, which was countered with} g6 $1 15. Bg4 Bc5 {, so White must have been happy to force a draw by} 16. Qxc5 Bxe6 17. Qxa7 Bxg4 18. Qa8+ Kd7 19. Qa4+ Kc8 20. Qa8+ {1/2-1/2 Drygalov - Afanasiev, Cheliabinsk Lozovatsky Memorial-A, 2022}) 13... Bxe6 14. Bxe6+ Qxe6 15. Qxe6+ fxe6 16. Kf1 $14) 11. Nf3 $5 $146 {A new idea not to force matters.} (11. Qh5 g6 $1 (11... hxg5 $2 12. Qxh8 Bd7 13. Qh3 $16 {T. Wang - S. Tsolakidou, Saint Louis 1000 IM 2nd, 2022}) 12. Nxe6 Bxe6 13. Bxg6 fxg6 14. Qe5 Rh7 15. Qxe6 Qxe6 16. Rxe6+ Re7 $11) 11... Bd7 12. Be3 a6 {Black is already in need of good advice.} (12... g6 13. Bd4 Rg8 14. Qd2 $16) (12... Qd6 13. Bd4 Be7 (13... O-O-O 14. Bxa7 $14) 14. Be5 Qb6 15. c3 O-O (15... O-O-O 16. Bxg7 $5 (16. a4 $5 a5 17. b4 $40) 16... Rhg8 17. Bxh6 Bd6 18. Be3 $14) 16. Bc2 $44 {[%cal Gd1d3]}) 13. c4 $1 dxc4 14. Be4 $1 O-O-O 15. Ne5 Be8 $1 (15... Kb8 16. Qd5 $1 c6 17. Qxc4 $16) (15... f5 16. Bd5 Bb5 17. Qf3 $16) 16. Qf3 Qb4 $1 17. a3 Qb5 (17... Qb3 18. Bd5 $16) 18. Rad1 Bd6 ({White is staying on top after} 18... Be7 {as well, for example} 19. Rxd8+ Nxd8 ({the compensation for the exchange after} 19... Bxd8 20. Nxf7 Rf8 21. Bd5 Bxf7 22. Bxe6+ Bxe6 23. Qxf8 {is arguable -} Qxb2 24. Rd1 Qf6 25. Qc5 $14) 20. Qg4+ Ne6 21. Ng6 $1 fxg6 22. Qxe6+ Bd7 23. Qxe7 Re8 24. Qxg7 (24. Bxb7+ $5 Kxb7 25. Qxg7 $14) 24... Rxe4 25. Qxg6 $14) 19. Rd5 Qb3 20. Nxf7 Bxf7 21. Qxf7 Ng5 22. Bxg5 hxg5 23. g3 Kb8 24. Qxg7 Rhf8 25. Qd4 $14 *

