{[%evp 0,45,38,26,18,26,24,11,11,-10,-7,-7,-14,-14,-15,5,14,22,13,7,43,52,47,23,23,25,25,33,33,52,52,52,52,37,37,35,26,-15,-9,10,33,26,31,15,28,14,8,15]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3 d5 8. exd5 O-O ({The immediate} 8... Bg4 $2 {is ill-timed because of} 9. f3 Bh5 10. Qe2+ $1 Be7 11. dxc6 O-O {and now} 12. Bf4 $1 (12. O-O $16 {Paravyan - Beerdsen, Titled Tuesday 1st Mar 2022}) 12... Re8 13. O-O-O $18) (8... Nxd5 9. O-O Nxc3 10. bxc3 Be7 11. Qf3 $16) (8... Qe7+ {It is unsound from a strategical point of view for Black to exchange the queens since White is trying to take advantage of the potentially better queenside pawn structure -} 9. Qe2 {and now:} Qxe2+ (9... cxd5 10. Qxe7+ Kxe7 (10... Bxe7 11. Nb5 Kd7 12. O-O c5 13. b3 $14) 11. a3 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Re8 13. Be3 Ng4 14. Bc5+ $14) (9... Nxd5 10. Bd2 Nxc3 11. Qxe7+ Kxe7 12. a3 $1 Ba5 13. b4 Bxb4 14. axb4 Nd5 15. O-O $16 {V. Bachin - K. Sek, Vladivostok, 2007.}) 10. Kxe2 {if} cxd5 {, then} (10... Nxd5 11. Nxd5 $1 cxd5 12. Bf4 c6 13. c3 Be7 14. b4 $1 $146 {An instructive new idea, aimed at the eventual Black's weaknesses. Such a simply looking endgame can be very unpleasant for the second player.} O-O (14... Be6 15. a4 Kd7 16. a5 Bf6 17. Kd2 $14) 15. Be3 a5 16. a3 $14 {Here, besides the better pawn structure, White's king is more active, which is a serious argument of his as well.}) 11. Nb5 $1 $36 {is rather unpleasant -} Kd8 12. Rd1 c6 13. Nd4 Kc7 14. c4 Re8+ 15. Kf1 Bg4 16. f3 Be6 17. Bf4+ $14 {Sutovsky - Jonkman, Groningen, 1994.}) 9. O-O Bg4 $5 {A fashionable line in the recent tournament practice, in which Black is trying to force matters.} (9... Nxd5 10. Ne4 $16) 10. f3 ({Another option is} 10. Ne2 cxd5 11. h3 Bh5 12. c4 {, where White is trying to fight for a slight edge in a quiet position.}) 10... Bh5 11. Bg5 cxd5 (11... Qd6 $5 {is another decent attempt, which has been discussed in high-level games:} 12. Qe1 (12. Kh1 Bxc3 13. bxc3 cxd5 14. Qd2 Bg6 15. Bf4 (15. Rad1 Rfe8 16. c4 Bxd3 17. Qxd3 dxc4 18. Qxc4 Qe6 19. Rd4 h6 20. Qxe6 Rxe6 21. Bxf6 Rxf6 $11 {1/2-1/2 V. Kovalev - H. Nakamura, Chess.com Rapid, 2022}) 15... Qc5 16. Be3 Qc6 17. Rfe1 Rfe8 $11) 12... Nxd5 {is the newly established tabiya and now:} 13. Bd2 (13. Ne4 Bxe1 14. Nxd6 Bb4 15. Nc4 Bc5+ $1 ({a refinement upon} 15... Rfe8 16. Rad1 f6 17. Bd2 a5 18. a3 Bxd2 19. Rxd2 $14 {1/2-1/2 Nepomniachtchi - Caruana, chess24.com INT rapid 2021}) 16. Kh1 Nb4 17. Bf5 Bg6 18. Bxg6 hxg6 $132) 13... Nf4 $5 $146 {A logical attempt to cause even more simplifications.} (13... Qc5+ 14. Qf2 Qxf2+ 15. Kxf2 Bc5+ $1 (15... Nxc3 16. Bxc3 Bxc3 17. bxc3 Bg6 18. Rab1 Rab8 19. Rfe1 $14) 16. Kg3 $1 {White will be able to retain the better pawn structure and, therefore, some edge.} a5 $5 (16... Bd6+ 17. f4 Rfe8 18. Rae1 Nb4 19. Be4 Bg6 20. Bxg6 hxg6 21. Rxe8+ Rxe8 22. Rc1 g5 $1 23. Kf3 gxf4 24. Bxf4 $14 {/=}) 17. Ne4 Bb6 18. Bc4 (18. c4 Ne3 $1 ({a clear improvement on} 18... Nb4 $6 19. Bxb4 axb4 20. c5 $14 {Paravyan - Oparin, Titled Tuesday 19th Jul, 2022}) 19. Rfe1 Nf5+ 20. Kh3 Rfd8 $132) 18... a4 19. Rad1 $14 {/=}) 14. Ne4 (14. Bxf4 Qxf4 15. Qe4 Qxe4 16. Nxe4 f5 17. Ng5) 14... Bxd2 15. Qxd2 Qd4+ 16. Kh1 Nxd3 17. cxd3 Rad8 18. Qf2 $1 {Black still has more weaknesses and should fight for equality in the long run.} Bg6 19. Rfd1 Bxe4 (19... Rfe8 20. Kg1 $14) 20. Qxd4 Rxd4 21. dxe4 Rfd8 22. Rxd4 Rxd4 23. b3 {It is now becoming clear that, in one way or another, this endgame will transform to 4 vs. 3 pawns on the kingside. White will have reasonable practical chances to convert, but such an ending is beyond the topic of our survey.} Kf8 (23... Rd2 24. h4 h5 25. Rc1 $14) 24. Kg1 Rd2 (24... Ke7 25. Rc1 Kd6 26. Rc2 $14 {/=}) 25. Rc1 Rxa2 26. Rxc6 $14 {/=}) 12. Bxf6 $5 {[%emt 0:00:15] The favorite line of the leading expert Paravyan. It also contains a nice trap.} ({It is not recommendable to reverse the move order -} 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. Bxf6 Qc5+ $1 14. Kh1 gxf6 {White has compensation, but not more after} 15. a3 Ba5 16. b4 Bxb4 17. axb4 Qxb4 $11) 12... Qxf6 13. Nxd5 Bc5+ 14. Kh1 Qxb2 15. Rb1 Qe5 (15... Qxa2 $2 {There are six games in my database and most of those players belong to the elite.} 16. Rb5 $1 {Black is in trouble:} c6 (16... Qa3 17. Qd2 c6 18. Ne7+ $1 (18. Ra5 Qb2 19. Qc3 Qxc3 20. Nxc3 Bb4 21. Rxh5 Bxc3 22. Bxh7+ Kh8 23. Be4+ Kg8 $14 {/=}) 18... Bxe7 19. Rxh5 {with powerful attack for White, as witnessed by} Rfd8 $8 (19... h6 $2 20. Rxh6 Rfd8 21. Bh7+ Kf8 22. Bf5 Kg8 23. Qf4 $18) (19... g6 $2 20. Qh6 $18) 20. Bxh7+ Kf8 21. Bd3 Kg8 22. f4 $40) 17. Nc3 Qa3 18. Nb1 $1 {Here is White's crafty trick!} cxb5 19. Nxa3 Bxa3 20. Bxb5 $16 {D. Paravyan - V. Kovalev, Chess.com Rapid, 2022}) 16. Re1 $5 {A fresh novelty, which settles yet another exciting trap.} ({The practice has seen} 16. f4 {, but it leads to a relatively easy draw after} Bxd1 17. fxe5 {and now:} Bg4 (17... Bh5 $2 18. Rb5 $1 c6 (18... Bb6 19. e6 $18) 19. Rxc5 cxd5 20. Rxd5 $16) 18. Nxc7 Rac8 19. Rb7 Rfd8 $1 (19... Bd7 $2 20. Na6 $1 Be6 21. Nxc5 Rxc5 22. Rxa7 $16 {R. Hovhannisyan - A. Neiksans, Tal Memorial, Riga, 2021}) 20. Nb5 (20. Na6 Bd4 21. Rfxf7 Bxe5 22. Rf1 Be6 $44) (20. e6 fxe6 21. Bc4 Rf8 $1 22. Rxf8+ Bxf8 23. h3 (23. Rxa7 Rd8 24. Bd3 Bf5 $132) 23... Bd6 24. hxg4 Rxc7 25. Rxc7 {1/2-1/2 Murzin - Rakhmanov, RUS-ch, Cheboksary 2022}) 20... Be6 21. Nd6 Bd5 22. Rb5 Rc7 23. a4 g6 {Black has ample compensation due to the pair of powerful bishops and White's pawn islands.}) 16... Qd6 $1 (16... Qd4 $2 {looks active and logical, but it is actually running into} 17. Rb4 $1 Bxb4 18. Bxh7+ Kxh7 19. Qxd4 Bxe1 20. Qe4+ Kh8 21. Qxe1 Rad8 22. Qa5 c6 23. Ne3 $16 {, which seems to be a technically winning position.}) 17. Ne7+ Kh8 18. Qe2 Bg6 ({Or} 18... Rab8 19. Qe4 Bg6 20. Nxg6+ hxg6 21. Rxb8 Rxb8 22. g3 $14 {/=}) 19. Nxg6+ hxg6 (19... fxg6 20. g3 Bb4 21. Red1 $14) 20. Qe5 $1 {At first sight, it is hard to believe, but I think it is not so pleasant to play as Black, since in this almost symmetrical position White has clear targets on the kingside.} Rab8 (20... Qxe5 $6 21. Rxe5 Bb6 (21... Bd6 22. Ra5 $14) 22. Rbe1 Rad8 23. g3 Kg8 24. Kg2 $14) 21. Rbd1 Kg8 22. g3 Rfd8 23. Kg2 $14 {/= Personally speaking, I would be happy to play this line myself, especially in various blitz and rapid competitions.} *

