{[%evp 0,35,26,26,17,17,17,11,11,-10,-10,1,1,1,1,1,-4,1,1,1,1,4,14,5,-11,-5,5,6,0,0,-8,-15,-16,-41,3,-1,-1,0]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3 d5 8. exd5 cxd5 9. O-O O-O 10. h3 {There are various move orders.} (10. Qf3 {usually leads to transpositions, but here, Black has an extra option in} Bg4 $5 11. Qg3 c5 $5 {(almost a novelty)} 12. Bg5 Bxc3 $1 {is practically liquidating to a draw after} (12... Be6 13. Rad1 (13. Rfd1 $1) 13... Bxc3 14. bxc3 c4 15. Bxc4 Ne4 16. Bxd8 Nxg3 17. hxg3 Rfxd8 18. Bb3 $14 {Xiong - Alavi Moghaddam, Titled Tuesday 10th Nov, 2020}) 13. bxc3 c4 $1 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Qxg4 (15. Bxh7+ Kxh7 16. Qxg4 Qxc3 17. Qf5+ Kg8 18. Qxd5 Rad8 19. Qc6 Rd2 $11) 15... cxd3 16. cxd3 Qxc3 17. Qf3 Rac8 $5 $11) 10... Rb8 $5 {interesting attempt to transfer rook by 6th rank} (10... c5 {looks principled, but at the same time it is not so easy to defend both hanging pawns.} 11. Qf3 Be6 (11... c4 $2 12. Bxc4 Bxc3 13. bxc3 Be6 14. Bd3 $16 {dropstoneDP - GmRamSoffer, Chess. com, 2022}) 12. Rd1 $1 Qe7 (12... Nd7 $2 {is a blunder -} 13. Nxd5 Ne5 14. Qg3 {(most probably this move has been overlooked)} Bxd5 15. Qxe5 $18 {dropstoneDP - artooon, Chess.com, 2022}) (12... Bxc3 13. bxc3 Qa5 14. Bg5 Ne4 ({Black has suffered on the dark squares after} 14... Nd7 15. Qg3 f6 16. Bh6 Rf7 17. Re1 Nf8 18. Bf4 {, as shown by} c4 19. Bf1 Bf5 20. Re2 Ng6 21. Rae1 Nxf4 22. Qxf4 Bg6 23. Qd6 Rff8 24. Re7 Bf7 25. R1e3 Qxa2 26. Rg3 Kh8 27. Qd7 Kg8 28. Qg4 g6 29. Qf4 Rab8 30. Qxf6 Rb1 {1-0 dropstoneDP - eljanov, Chess.com, 2022}) 15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. Qg3 {Kramnik has proved in his prime time how tricky such middlegames with opposite-colored bishops can be.} f6 17. Bh6 Rf7 18. Rd6 Re8 19. a4 e3 20. Qxe3 Bd7 21. Qg3 Bf5 22. Rxf6 Bg6 23. Rxf7 Kxf7 24. Bf4 {1-0 dropstoneDP - DetskiSad, Chess.com, 2022.}) (12... h6 $6 {looks passive. Much more principled is} 13. Na4 $1 (13. Ne2 Qe7 14. c3 Ba5 15. Nf4 Bc7 16. Re1 $6 (16. b4 $132) 16... Qd6 $1 $15 {jefferyx - peonrojo150, Chess.com, 2022}) 13... Nd7 14. Qg3 Kh8 15. c3 Ba5 16. Bf4 $16) 13. Qg3 {Black position is a bit precarious and he has to be on alert for all sorts of tactics.} Rfd8 (13... Rfe8 14. Bb5 $1 (14. Bg5 c4 15. Bf1 Bd6 $4 (15... Bxc3 16. bxc3 Ne4 17. Bxe7 Nxg3 18. Bc5 Nxf1 19. Kxf1 a6 $14 {/=}) 16. Bxf6 $18 (16. Qh4 $4 {dropstoneDP - rasmussvane, Chess.com, 2022})) 14... Rec8 15. Bg5 d4 16. Na4 a6 17. Bd3 $14) 14. Bh6 Nh5 15. Qg5 Qxg5 16. Bxg5 Nf6 17. Na4 (17. Rab1 $5) 17... c4 18. c3 $1 Bf8 19. Bc2 $14 {/=}) (10... Be6 11. Qf3 c5 {is transposing to the lines from above.}) (10... Bb7 {In my view this bishop is a bit misplaced here, especially before White has played Qf3.} 11. Bg5 (11. Qf3 Rb8 $5 12. Bg5 Be7 13. Rfe1 d4 14. Ne4 Nxe4 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. Bxe4 Bxe4 17. Rxe4 Qc5 18. b3 Rfe8 $14 {/= Areshchenko - Ponomariov, ESP-chT, Linares, 2017}) 11... h6 (11... Be7 12. Re1 h6 13. Bh4 d4 14. Nb5 $1 (14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Ne4 Be7 16. Nd2 Rb8 17. Qg4 Bb4 18. Re2 Bxd2 19. Rxd2 Qg5 20. Qxg5 hxg5 {G. Antal - G. Papp, Hungary, 2013,} 21. b4 $14) 14... c5 15. Qe2 $14) (11... c5 12. Qf3 h6 13. Bh4 ({Black's move 11 has cut the way back for Bb4 to its usual d6-square and} 13. Bxf6 $5 Qxf6 14. Qxf6 gxf6 15. Ne2 $14 {/= is an attempt to exploit this}) 13... Re8 14. Rfe1 Qb6 15. a3 $5 (15. Rxe8+ $143 Rxe8 16. Na4 Qc6 17. Bxf6 c4 $1 18. Bc3 Qxa4 $132 {Abdusattorov - Nabaty, Aeroflot op-A 18th, 2019}) 15... Bxc3 16. bxc3 $14 {/=}) 12. Bh4 g5 13. Bg3 Ne4 {deserves tests, e. g.} 14. Qh5 $5 Qf6 $1 15. Bxc7 $36) 11. Be3 $5 {A prophylactic measure against Black's strategical idea.} ({In reply to} 11. Qf3 {Black has} Rb6 $1 {and it turns out that this rook is very well placed and can potentially fight for the e-file via the e6-square.} 12. Bg5 (12. a3 Be7 13. Bg5 Bb7 $132) (12. Na4 Re6 13. a3 Bd6 14. Bf4 Ne4 $132) 12... h6 13. Bxf6 Rxf6 14. Qxd5 Bxc3 15. Qxd8 Rxd8 16. bxc3 Ba6 17. Rad1 Rfd6 18. Rfe1 Bxd3 19. cxd3 Rxd3 {1/2-1/2 J. Degraeve - E. Bacrot, FRA-chT, Brest, 2019.}) 11... c5 $1 (11... Re8 $2 {is blundering the mentioned pawn -} 12. Bxa7 Rb7 13. Bd4 $16 {dropstoneDP - SVODMEVKO, lichess.org, 2022}) (11... Be7 $6 {should be met by the same} 12. Bxa7 {After} Rxb2 {dropstoneDP - Duhless, Chess.com, 2022, White keeps the better prospects by means of} 13. a4 Rb7 14. Bd4 c5 15. Be5 $14) 12. a3 Bxc3 13. bxc3 c4 {Black has to play resolutely in order to keep his center intact.} (13... Qd6 14. Qf3 Rb2 15. Rad1 $14 {dropstoneDP - BrandonJacobson, Chess.com, 2022}) (13... Qa5 14. c4 Be6 15. cxd5 Nxd5 16. Bd2 $14 {dropstoneDP - lonelyqueen0, Chess.com, 2022.}) 14. Be2 a6 $1 $146 {Black's vulnerable pawns might counterbalance the doubled c-pawns.} (14... Qa5 15. Bd4 Ne4 16. Bf3 (16. Bg4 $5 f5 17. Bh5 $14) 16... Bf5 17. Qc1 Bg6 18. h4 $36 {with a dream position for White, dropstoneDP - SantoBlue, Chess. com 2022}) (14... Ne4 $6 15. Qd4 $1 (15. Bxa7 Nxc3 16. Qe1 {with a quick draw in Tukhaev - Ragger, Wch Blitz, St Petersburg, 2018} Qe7 17. Qxc3 Qxa7 18. a4 Re8 $132) 15... a6 16. Bf3 $14 (16. Bxc4 $5 $14)) 15. Qd2 ({The dark-squared bishop can prefer another diagonal -} 15. Bf4 {, thus leaving the d4-square to the queen. Here is an interesting sample line} Rb6 (15... Rb2 16. Qc1 Rb6 17. Rd1 Rc6 18. Bf3 $14 {/=}) 16. Bf3 Bf5 17. Re1 Be4 (17... h6 18. Re5 $14 {/=}) 18. Bxe4 Nxe4 19. Qd4 Rf6 20. Bh2 $1 Nxf2 $132) 15... Bf5 16. Rab1 h6 17. Bf3 Re8 18. Bd4 $14 {/= I believe that in a practical game White's position has to be preferred due to the powerful Bd4.} *

