{[%evp 0,61,26,26,26,17,17,19,14,-10,-10,1,1,1,1,1,-4,1,-4,4,-4,7,10,4,2,-11,21,-15,-5,5,0,0,0,13,0,-30,4,-6,-6,-3,6,7,12,-46,0,0,0,-23,-1,-6,0,0,-7,5,21,46,35,39,37,8,9,9,23,12]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3 d5 8. exd5 cxd5 9. O-O O-O 10. h3 c6 ({Both} 10... h6 11. Qf3 Re8 12. Bf4 c6) ({and} 10... Re8 11. Qf3 c6 {are about to transpose to lines, which will be examined a bit later.}) 11. Qf3 Bd6 (11... Re8 12. Bf4 Bd6 ({apart from the common text move, the practice has also seen} 12... Nd7 $5 {(a rare, but not a bad plan)} 13. Rfe1 Nc5 14. Rxe8+ Qxe8 15. Bf1 Ne6 $1 16. Be5 Bf8 17. Re1 {1/2-1/2 R. Mulde - F. Lang, ICCF email, 2019} Nc5 18. Qd1 $1 Qd8 19. Ne2 Ba6 20. b3 $14 {/=}) (12... h6 13. Rfe1 Rxe1+ 14. Rxe1 Be6 15. Rd1 $5 Bd6 16. Ne2 Rb8 {Ganguly - Vidit, Saint Louis Fall-A, 2022} 17. b3 $1 c5 18. Bc1 $5 $14) (12... Qe7 13. Ne2 $5 Ne4 14. a3 Bc5 15. b4 Bb6 16. Rae1 $14) 13. b3 $5 (13. Rfe1 {is the main move, but I have decided in general to avoid the exchanges along the e-file.}) 13... Be6 14. Ne2 Bxf4 (14... a5 15. a4 Bxf4 16. Qxf4 Qb6 17. Nd4 c5 18. Nb5 Re7 19. Rfe1 $14 {/= Sneddon - Brunori, ICCF email, 2020}) 15. Nxf4 Qd6 16. Rfd1 Bd7 17. Rac1 $5 (17. c4 d4 $132) 17... Qa3 (17... Re5 18. c4 Rae8 19. Ne2 $14 {/=}) 18. c3 $1 h6 ({an important line goes on with} 18... Qxa2 19. b4 $1 h6 20. Ra1 Qb2 21. Rdb1 Qd2 22. Rc1 $36) 19. Bb1 $14 {/=}) (11... Rb8 12. Bf4 Bd6 13. b3 {seems to favour White:} Rb4 (13... Be6 14. Ne2 $5 c5 15. Rad1 Re8 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. Nf4 Qc7 18. Rfe1 $1 (18. Nxe6 $6 Rxe6 19. c3 Qa5 $132 {Przybylski - Hjartarson, Wch Rapid, Berlin, 2015}) 18... Qb6 19. Re5 $36) 14. Ne2 $1 {A typical reaction against the aggressive Rb8-b4 idea.} Bxf4 (14... Re8 15. c4 $5 Bxf4 16. Nxf4 Ba6 17. Rfd1 Qc7 18. Re1 $5 Re5 $2 (18... Rbb8 19. cxd5 Bxd3 20. Nxd3 cxd5 21. Rac1 $14) 19. Nh5 $1 Qe7 20. Nxf6+ gxf6 21. Qg3+ Kf8 22. f4 $18 {D. Kerigan - R. Simon, Basel, 2018}) 15. Nxf4 Qd6 16. c4 $14 {does not yield Black the desired equality either -} a5 (16... Re8 17. Rfe1 Bd7 18. Rxe8+ Bxe8 19. Re1 $16 {jefferyx - DenLaz, Chess.com, 2020}) 17. Rfd1 Be6 (17... a4 18. Bc2 axb3 19. Bxb3 Be6 {So far jefferyx - vladislavkovalev, Chess. com, 2022, here the simplest is} 20. cxd5 cxd5 21. Nxd5 Bxd5 22. Bxd5 Nxd5 23. Rxd5 $14) 18. Rac1 a4 19. Bc2 axb3 20. Bxb3 h6 21. Rc2 Rd8 22. Rcd2 $14) (11... a5 {might be a waste of time -} 12. Na4 Be6 13. Be3 Re8 14. Rad1 $14 {dropstoneDP - BrandonJacobson, Chess.com, 2022}) (11... h6 $5 {I have played this small prophylactic move myself.} 12. Bf4 Bd6 13. Rfe1 Bxf4 $5 (13... Be6 {looks premature.} 14. Ne2 $1 c5 15. Rad1 Rb8 16. b3 Re8 17. Bxd6 (17. c3 a5 (17... Bxf4 $6 18. Nxf4 Qd6 19. Bc4 $16 {Xiong - Quesada Perez, PNWCC Online blitz, 2020}) 18. Bc2 Rb6 19. Bxd6 Rxd6 20. Nf4 d4 (20... Bd7 $142 $1 21. Qg3 Rxe1+ 22. Rxe1 Bb5 $132) 21. Nxe6 Rexe6 22. Rxe6 Rxe6 23. Bd3 $14 {and this bishop will be annoying from the c4-square, Xiong - Kamsky, Titled Tuesday 03rd May, 2022}) 17... Qxd6 {Paravyan - Martinez Alcantara, Chess.com Rapid, 2022} 18. Nf4 Rbd8 {Erigaisi - Tabatabaei, Sitges, 2019, and now} 19. Bb5 $1 Re7 20. c4 $1 d4 21. Nd3 $36) (13... Rb8 {A popular plan, but Black may land in a very unpleasant position in this particular situation.} 14. b3 Rb4 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. Qe3 $1 {A very typical resource in this line.} Rb7 ({a neat point of White's move order is the possibility to meet} 16... d4 {with} 17. Ne4 $1 dxe3 18. Nxd6 exf2+ 19. Kxf2 Be6 20. Rad1 $16) 17. Na4 Be6 18. Rad1 Re8 19. Nc5 Rbe7 20. Qd4 $14 {Anton Guijarro - Tang, Chess24 Banter Blitz Cup, 2020}) 14. Qxf4 c5 $1 {A very concrete approach. The hanging central pawns are looking vulnerable, but Black is just in time to protect everything, as I have proved in my recent game against Geoffrey in Titled Tuesday.} 15. a4 $5 (15. Rad1 Bd7 $1 (15... Qb6 $5 16. b3 Bd7 17. Bf5 Bc6 18. Rd3 Rfe8 19. Rxe8+ Rxe8 20. Re3 Rxe3 21. fxe3 Qd8 $11 {Xiong - Salem, Speed Chess, 2022}) 16. Bf5 Bc6 17. Ne4 Nxe4 18. Bxe4 Qb8 $1 {The ultimate equalizer.} 19. Qxb8 Rfxb8 20. Bxd5 Bxd5 21. Rxd5 Rxb2 $11 {1/2-1/2 Xiong - Eljanov, Titled Tuesday 06th Dec, 2022}) (15. b4 g5 $1 16. Qg3 cxb4 17. Nb5 Nh5 $5 18. Qe5 Nf4 $132) 15... Bd7 ({The most natural continuation, the alternatives are inferior -} 15... Qb6 16. b3 Bd7 17. Nb5 Rad8 18. Bf1 $14 {/=}) (15... a6 16. a5 Be6 17. b3 $14) 16. b4 $5 (16. b3 Qb8 (16... Qa5 17. Nb5) 17. Qxb8 Raxb8 18. Nb5 a5 $11) 16... cxb4 17. Qxb4 Rb8 18. Qf4 Qa5 $1 (18... Rc8 19. Ne2) 19. Nb5 $14 {/= with a small, but lasting initiative.}) 12. Re1 Bd7 $5 {The most flexible option - Black is developing without committing to any kind of possible targets (Rb8) or semi-useful moves like h6.} ({As said, the plan with} 12... Rb8 {is very typical and popular at the same time. However, it seems slightly inaccurate here, since the rook's position also has drawbacks. Thus the a-pawn is temporarily unprotected and the counterplay along the b-file is often quite limited after the natural} 13. b3 {and now:} Re8 (13... Rb4 $6 14. Ne2 $5 (14. a3 Rb8 15. Bf4 h6 16. Na4 $14 {dropstoneDP - bubacik, Chess.com, 2019}) 14... Re8 15. Bd2 $14) (13... h6 14. Bb2 Re8 {dropstoneDP - F19HT3R, Chess.com, 2022} 15. Rad1 Rb7 16. Ne2 $36) (13... Be6 14. Bb2 Nd7 15. Ne2 Qg5 16. Bc1 $5 Qf6 17. Qxf6 Nxf6 18. Bf4 $14) (13... Bb4 $6 14. Bb2 $1 h6 (14... d4 15. Ne4 $1 Bxe1 16. Rxe1 Nd5 (16... c5 17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 18. Qh5 $1 $16) 17. Bxd4 $16) 15. Rad1 $14) 14. Rxe8+ Qxe8 15. Bf4 Qe7 16. Bxd6 (16. Na4 $5 $14) 16... Qxd6 17. Qe3 $1 {while emphasizing the abovementioned insecurity of the a-pawn, White would rather take the central dark squares under control.} ({An automatical development like} 17. Re1 Bd7 18. Kf1 c5 $132 {did not pose any problems to Black in Skripchenko - Sharafiev, EU-Cup Online Final, 2021}) 17... d4 (17... c5 $6 {exposes this pawn voluntarily to grave danger after} 18. Na4) 18. Ne4 Nxe4 19. Qxe4 g6 20. Re1 $14) (12... Re8 13. Rxe8+ Qxe8 14. Bf4 Qe7 15. Na4 (15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. Qe3 {dropstoneDP - Sebastian, Chess.com 2022, can be met here by} c5 $1 17. Na4 c4 18. Bf1 Qb4 $132) 15... c5 16. c4 $1 (16. b3 $6 Bd7 17. Nc3 Bc6 $132 {is not the way to reveal the problem with the delayed development of Ra8, namely the pin along the big diagonal, dropstoneDP - Sebastian, Chess.com, 2022}) 16... Bxf4 17. Qxf4 Ba6 (17... d4 $6 18. Qg5 $16) (17... Bd7 18. Qc7 $1 $16) 18. Rd1 d4 19. Rd2 Rc8 20. Re2 Qc7 21. Qe5 $14) (12... Be6 13. Ne2 $5 Re8 14. Bd2 $5 {I like this flexible set-up very much.} c5 15. c3 Rb8 16. b3 $14 {/= Black's center can be undermined at any appropriate moment.}) 13. Bg5 {Here I have decided to deviate from the most typical f4-square for this bishop.} ({Black is ready to meet} 13. Bf4 {with the comfortable set-up} Qc7 $1 14. Ne2 (14. Bg5 Bh2+ 15. Kh1 Be5 16. Re2 Rfe8 $132) 14... Rfe8 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. c4 Re5 $132) 13... h6 {A bit more precise move order in comparison to 13...Rb8, because, after the latter, White has an extra option to retreat to the d2-square.} (13... Rb8 14. b3 h6 15. Bh4 (15. Bd2 $5) 15... Rb4 $5 (15... Re8 {transposes to the main text}) 16. Bxf6 (16. Bg3 Qc7 17. Bxd6 Qxd6 $132) 16... Qxf6 17. Qxf6 gxf6 18. Nd1 $1 {This structure can sometimes arise earlier, when White opts for Qf3-Bg5 plan in different move orders. I think it is more pleasant for the latter to handle it, an opinion, that practical games have proved.} Be5 19. Rc1 a5 (19... Rd8 20. Ne3 Kf8 21. c3 $1 (21. Ng4 $6 {is premature -} Bxg4 (21... Bc3 $1 22. Re2 h5 $132 {is even better}) 22. hxg4 Rxg4 23. g3 $44 h5 24. Kg2 Kg7 25. Kh3 Rh8 $6 (25... Kf8 26. Re3 $44) 26. f4 $14 Bb2 {dropstoneDP - BuLolo, Chess.com, 2022} 27. Rcd1 $16) 21... Rb7 22. Ng4 $14 {/=}) 20. Ne3 h5 (20... a4 21. Ng4 $5 Bxg4 22. hxg4 Rxg4 23. g3 $44 h5 ({Black is well-advised to be more cautious, for instance} 23... Rb4 24. Kg2 Kg7 25. Bf5 Rfb8 26. Bd7 R4b6 27. Rh1 Rd8 28. Bf5 Rb4 29. Rh5 $44) 24. Kg2 h4 25. Kh3 Rb4 26. f4 Bc3 27. Rg1 $36) 21. Be2 $5 h4 22. Bg4 Be6 23. Nf5 $14 {/=}) 14. Bh4 Rb8 $5 {Now this idea is much more justified, since Black can attack the dark-squared bishop along the 4th rank.} 15. b3 Re8 (15... Rb4 {transposes to another important position, which has already been examined in the annotations to 13....Rb8.}) 16. Rxe8+ Qxe8 17. Kf1 $5 {The only way to regain control over the e-file.} ({Harmless is} 17. Rd1 Qe5 $1 18. Bg3 Qe7 19. Na4 Re8 20. c4 d4 (20... Be6 $5 $132) 21. Bxd6 Qxd6 $132 {Shuvalova- Lysyj, Obninsk, 2022.}) 17... Rb4 18. Bg3 Qf8 {A necessary precaution.} (18... Qb8 $143 19. a3 Bxg3 20. fxg3 Rb7 21. Na4 Qd6 22. b4 a5 23. Nc5 $14 {/=}) 19. Re1 a5 {White is faced with a choice, in either case, Black has to play carefully in order to keep the balance. I think it is still easier to play as White.} 20. Kg1 $5 (20. Qe3 $5 Rb8 (20... Bxg3 21. Qxg3 Qb8 22. Na4 Qxg3 23. fxg3 Kf8 24. g4 Be6 25. Nc5 Bc8 26. Kf2 Nd7 27. Na4 $14) 21. Na4 Re8 22. Bxd6 Qxd6 23. Qb6 {is worth checking, for example} Rxe1+ 24. Kxe1 Qe5+ (24... Qh2 25. Nc5) 25. Kd1 $5 (25. Kf1 Bf5 $1 $132) 25... Qh2 $1 (25... Bf5 26. Bxf5 Qxf5 27. Qe3 $14) 26. Nc5 Be8 27. Qxa5 $5 Qxg2 28. Qc3 Qxf2 29. b4 $13) 20... Rb8 21. Bh4 Re8 22. Rxe8 Qxe8 23. Kf1 $5 {A second arrival at this square.} Qe5 24. Bg3 Qe7 25. Bxd6 Qxd6 26. Qe3 d4 27. Ne4 Nxe4 28. Qxe4 Kf8 {1/2-1/2 Muukkonen - Kuosmanen, ICCF email, 2013. A possible continuation is} 29. Qh7 Qe5 30. Qh8+ Ke7 31. Qa8 $14 {/= and some precision is still required from Black.} *

